"Ajahn" (Thai: อาจารย์) is "teacher" in the Thai language derived from the (Pali) word ācārya. Ajahn is often used interchangeably with Kruu (Tahi: ครู) although it is often more respectful and reserved for older teachers or post-secondary teachers.
In the Thai Theravada tradition, it is generally a title given to a Bhikkhu who has been fully ordained for ten rain retreats (ten years). More senior monks are also referred to by the title Luang Por (Thai: หลวงพ่อ) "Venerable Father."

